    <h2>IP and the Web</h2>
    <p>
        When you submit a request in a web browser for the site <code>https://www.google.com</code>, many things happen under the hood 
        in order for your computer to understand what you're asking of it. The first thing it does is figure out <em>where</em> 
        <code>www.google.com</code> is located. It does this by making use of <abbr title="DNS">Domain Name System</abbr> to
        convert the domain name into an IP address. You can do this manually on your computer using <code>nslookup</code>:
    </p>

    <pre><code>
$ nslookup www.google.com
Server:               127.0.0.53
Address:        127.0.0.53#53

Non-authoritative answer:
Name:   www.google.com
Address: 172.217.11.164
Name:   www.google.com
Address: 2607:f8b0:4007:804::2004
    </code></pre>

    <p>
        With this information, your computer knows to send the HTTP request to a computer with an IP address of <code>172.217.11.164</code>. 
        The computer will send the packet to its gateway router which will look at the IP address for <code>www.google.com</code> and determine 
        how to route the request in order to get it to its destination efficiently.
    </p>

